Wildfires started by lightning, fireworks and vehicle exhaust pipes
were combated over the July 4 weekend in various parts of the country.
The areas most affected were: Utah's Zion National Park; Montana's
Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness Area and Custer National Forest;
Wyoming's Bridger-Teton and Shoshone National Forests, and Yellowstone
Park; California's Yosemite Park and Los Padres National Forest;
Michigan's Hiawatha National Forest; and various wildlands in Kentucky
and Tennessee.  No injuries or serious property damage were reported.
Forest Service policy is to allow wilderness fires to burn unless they
threaten rails or structures or are about to spread outside the
wilderness area.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880705-0109"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

Firefighters in various states battled holiday weekend fires, which
blackened more than 6,000 acres of forest and wilderness areas.  Those
areas most affected were: California's Stanislaus National Forest;
Utah's Zion National Park; Montana's Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness and
Custer National Forest; Wyoming's Shoshone National Forest and
Yellowstone Park; Michigan's Hiawatha National Park; and Arizona's
Tonto National Forest.  Forest Service policy allows wilderness fires
to burn unless they threaten trails or structures, or threaten to burn
outside the wilderness boundary.  Cooler temperatures and calmer wind
helped control fires in Montana.

Rain slowed or damped the fires in Wyoming's National Park and Forest
areas.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880705-0018"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

Rainfall helped firefighters control wildfires in Wyoming's Shoshone
National Forest and Yellowstone National Park, and in California's
Yosemite National Park over the weekend.  Four firefighting crews were
expected from Colorado, Utah and South Dakota to reinforce
firefighters in Wyoming.  At Yellowstone, firefighters reported the
fires 90 percent contained by Monday.  The cause of a fire in nearby
Stanislaus National Forest was a "bottle rocket".  A fire in
Michigan's Hiawatha National Forest was brought under control Monday.
The Fourth of July was no holiday for firefighters from national
forests in Wisconsin, Minnesota, Idaho and other states who were
shipped to Michigan.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880801-0195"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

Forest officials for Missouri's Mark Twain Forest believe the problem
of arson is often rooted in some regional traditions.  A
psychologist's study found economic and even aesthetic reasons why
some people start forest fires.  The tradition stretches across the
southern United States.  Accordingly, in the springtime, people used
to burn the woods to allow grass to grow.  A policy of open grazing on
any open land was allowed in the Ozarks into the 1960s.  Subsistence
farmers claimed fire helped control ticks, snakes, disease, and
encroachment of trees on to grazing land.

Some people enjoyed the smell of smoke in the spring air.</SUM>

