The following is a brief look at forest fires in the Western states.
Alaska: 2.1 million acres are smoldering but the fires are not active;
Idaho: 17 major blazes are underway, mostly threatening in Star Valley
and Eagle Bar; Montana: One large fire is burning in the Scapegoat
Wilderness, and two in the Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness; Oregon: the
biggest forest fire is the Tepee Butte fire in the Wallowa-Whitman
National Forest; Utah: fires are under control near Pineview
Reservoir; Wyoming: fires are burning around Yellowstone Park at North
Fork and Clover-Mist; and Huck and Mink Creek in Bridger-Teton
National Forest.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ880923-0163"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

Less than seven weeks after the worst fire ever recorded in
Yellowstone National Park, the Park's environmental researchers are
monitoring what they term amazing steps the forest is taking to renew
itself.  The research should play a major role in a new debate over
whether to reforest burnt areas or let nature take its course.
Critics of the "natural burn" policy say controlled burning, selective
logging, and reforestation are a better way to manage forests.  Park
researchers hope that the evidence being gathered will testify to the
forest's ability to renew itself as it has for the past 10,000
years.</SUM>

<SUM
