So far this season, 31,000 brush and timber fires have been reported
in seven Western states and Alaska and Georgia.  1,111,000 acres have
burned so far compared to 765,000 acres last season.  In the West, the
fires were fought in Utah's Diamond Park and Vinta Canyon; Northern
California's Sierra foothills; Colorado's drought-stricken mountains
and eastern plains; Wyoming's Bridger-Teton National Forest; Arizona's
Mount Graham, Peloncillo and Rincon Mountains areas; and New Mexico's
Gila National Forest.  Four large fires burned in interior Alaska, one
burned in Georgia's Okeefeenokee Swamp, and another in north central
Washington.  Firefighters have contended with wind and high
temperatures.</SUM>


<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP881216-0017"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

A panel reporting to the secretaries of Agriculture and Interior
recommended a moratorium in the government's "let it burn" policy in
order for the Forest Service and National Park Service to refine fire
management plans.  The panel experts said there were environmental
benefits to letting parks and wilderness areas burn, but in some cases
the social and economic effects may be unacceptable. The report said:
fire management plans should conform to departmental policies,
employees should understand the policies, a common vocabulary should
be used, and there should be agreement between agencies beforehand of
what to do if fires move across administrative boundaries.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA070189-0080"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="G">      

Firefighters got the upper hand Friday on brush fires in the Cleveland
National Forest near Lake Elsinore and in the rugged terrain of the
Antelope Valley.  The Lake Elsinore fire appeared to be caused by
people near a roadside store across the Orange County line.
Firefighters along the Orange-Riverside County line are battling
lingering flames inside the rugged San Mateo Wilderness.  The Antelope
Valley fire was contained 100% but it claimed 2,250 acres along the
outskirts of Elizabeth Lake and Green Valley.  Six structures were
burned, including one home, and more than 300 firefighters battled the
blaze for three days.</SUM>

<SUM
